WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.540 --> 00:00:04.080
Hi, and welcome to designing Open Democracy podcast.

2
00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:11.720
This is a retrospective of an event called Citizens' Democracy which was held on the 21st of October 2017.

3
00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:18.740
The venue sponsor for this event was York Butter Factory which is a co-working space right at the centre of Melbourne.

4
00:00:18.740 --> 00:00:26.320
This was a question and answer session that was held after Nicholas Gruen and Hubertus Hofkirchner gave their speech.

5
00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:31.940
So, if you have not listened to their speech, I recommend you to listen to them now.

6
00:00:31.940 --> 00:00:37.680
Some of the questions may be interested is, How do you introduce this idea to the general public?

7
00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:43.320
What sort of results do you need in the next election before you can demonstrate to the public that this system can work?

8
00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:48.540
Is there an algorithm to help select citizen juries to make it as representative as possible?

9
00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:51.900
Have you heard of any kind of bureaucratic appointment systems?

10
00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:54.600
How would your system avoid corruption and manipulation?

11
00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:59.020
Citizens can deal with issues, but are they dealing with the right issues?

12
00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:02.720
How will citizens' jury work within existing systems?

13
00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:07.080
How do you hold citizens' juries accountable and representative?

14
00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:10.500
Are you suggesting to have citizen juries replace the Senate?

15
00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:15.780
And finally, what are the main factors for the acceptance of citizen juries?

16
00:01:15.780 --> 00:01:18.160
Did the press humanise the citizen juries?

17
00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:25.500
So, without further ado, Nicholas Merridge will start the question and answer session right now.

18
00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:30.040
Hi.

19
00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:43.140
When you were talking about people aren't engaged to be involved in thinking about democracy, I think perhaps that's because they're not aware that they think they are in a democracy, they're not aware that they're actually not.

20
00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:51.980
And the big reason is the media does not sort of, does not tell them what the actual choices are.

21
00:01:51.980 --> 00:02:01.520
It tells them more what the politicians or that constant media steal comes out every evening and in the papers.

22
00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:12.760
So it's something like what you're talking about sounds really interesting, but how would you get it through to the people when they're not aware that there's a problem in the first place?

23
00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:24.120
How would you get it to the media they're not going to go against their kind of, their liberal, labor kind of people who are in charge?

24
00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:24.560
Yeah, okay.

25
00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:28.260
Yeah, the problem is correct, yes?

26
00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:35.020
So people are not aware that they're not in a democracy, and it's a very complex, almost philosophical subject.

27
00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:42.060
We cannot blame the media for it, because here, the party system and the media has the same interest.

28
00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:47.240
The politicians want to emotionalize the electors, so that nine second soundbites work.

29
00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:53.600
And the media is also interested in emotion, because that's what sells media.

30
00:02:54.280 --> 00:03:02.700
So it's a devilish survey, and the solution is one of these three points I said in the end.

31
00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:11.360
We as deliberative democrats must not just propose to introduce deliberative democracy.

32
00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:32.620
We must before the elections do three, five, such Citizens Juries, so that our deliberative party can communicate to the people, to the media, what is the people's position, what's the general will on immigration, on finances, on education, on social, on unemployment.

33
00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:37.780
So if we can communicate that, then resolve the problem.

34
00:03:37.780 --> 00:03:47.460
And of course, we can tell people, and that's a strong argument in the background, we can tell people, this is not just party strategy, this is actually what people want.

35
00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:50.140
But I think it's a hygiene factor.

36
00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:51.260
It's not motivated.

37
00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:54.120
So it tells us that the process was okay.

38
00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:57.780
But it's a secondary aspect for the people.

39
00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:06.880
And so if we do those 3 to 5 Citizens Juries before the next elections, I'm quite sure we have the right topics, and media will write about it.

40
00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:24.360
Hi, I was just wondering, with your, in your country, what sort of result would you need in the next elections before you could actually get a representative into the parliament to be able to then demonstrate to the masses that the system could work?

41
00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:31.800
Here in Austria, it's 4 percent, both on the national as well as on the federal level.

42
00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:37.900
And since we did get already 1 percent, I think we're fairly confident to know how to make up the difference.

43
00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:47.000
Is there an algorithm or something that you have figured out about how to select a Citizens Juries?

44
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.920
Is there a way that you have figured out of making it as representative as possible?

45
00:04:54.680 --> 00:05:05.920
Yeah, we have a two-stage process which expands the one which for instance in, I read about the Melbourne Citizens Jury project.

46
00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:14.280
So I'm actually a little bit disappointed that not more people are sitting there because he really thinks it was a good success, the Financial Planning Jury.

47
00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:15.980
I don't know how many of you guys know that one?

48
00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:21.620
No, this is an important one.

49
00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:28.020
The New Democracy Foundation in Sydney, run by Australian entrepreneur, Conn.

50
00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:32.400
John Annetis and managed by a guy called Ian Walker.

51
00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:34.760
Yeah, well, Ian Walker.

52
00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:40.300
And they organized Citizens Juries in Melbourne.

53
00:05:40.300 --> 00:05:47.520
Melbourne, Central, when the council went off bankrupt, it was about two years ago.

54
00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:57.920
And I understand that the conditions could be salted because had they increased the taxes, people would have gone, wouldn't have liked that, if you like higher taxes.

55
00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:09.740
And had they cut social services or city services, civic services, I think the opposition would also have enjoyed the opportunity to get people on the street to protest.

56
00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:13.260
So they decided to put New Democracy in charge.

57
00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:32.100
And what New Democracy did as a selection process to answer the questioners' question was to follow the council, the council sent out 5,000 invitations, 500 came back and said they were interested to participate in the in the in the citizen council, I mean, the citizen jury.

58
00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:42.860
And then they used sortition, random draws, to make a representative sample of 42 people.

59
00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:53.680
So, half were women, half were men, there was lower income, middle income, high income, there were people who rented, people who owned, small business owners, employees.

60
00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:55.760
And I understand it worked perfectly well.

61
00:06:57.160 --> 00:07:17.660
That group, after six weeks, came up with a financial plan, using the council's proposals, which seemed to have put Melbourne back on track, and voted for things which would have caused the designation of your Melbourne mayor otherwise.

62
00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:21.760
They voted to increase the tax, because it was necessary.

63
00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:33.940
They voted to abandon certain high-expense, multimillion development of some old market space, which I think some lobbies put pressure on them.

64
00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:37.520
So let's take a look at that.

65
00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:40.360
Anyway, so we are changing that a little bit.

66
00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:52.280
In as far as we don't just want to allow anybody in, we have this mechanism whereby we compare, we have this survey phase first, where everybody can chip in.

67
00:07:52.280 --> 00:07:59.620
So not just those 42 people, but anybody who has a sense they want to talk about the topic can.

68
00:07:59.620 --> 00:08:09.460
And out of all these people who also say they volunteer for the Citizens Juries, we then find out who did good predictions and who did not so good.

69
00:08:09.460 --> 00:08:17.220
So in addition to just taking those people who volunteered, we also preselect who is a good decision maker.

70
00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:26.660
That's very important because very often in these political processes, you have a high number of people who are just nuts, psychos.

71
00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:29.560
It's really astonishing.

72
00:08:30.620 --> 00:08:42.700
And however, with the prediction mechanism, we have now seen in two rounds that those people really go fall down completely because they think all kinds of crazy things will happen, which of course never do happen.

73
00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:52.220
And so the rationale, the more thinking people come up stream, and that's also part of how we identify collective intelligence, small intelligence.

74
00:08:53.800 --> 00:09:01.480
But still, amongst these people, the sortition, the drawing of lots is again then representative.

75
00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:07.540
So of those clever decision makers, we again take half women, half men, low women, high income, and so on and so forth.

76
00:09:07.540 --> 00:09:11.680
I hope I was able to answer your question in a way that is neither the longer answer.

77
00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:26.200
I'm developing a theory that looks at the whole of government in respect to democracy and the way that government functions as far as getting things done.

78
00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:42.760
At the moment, it seems one of the major problems in respect to our democracy is that you have the parties and then the representatives of the parties and then the bureaucracy in respect to actually getting things done.

79
00:09:42.760 --> 00:10:00.700
So what I'm proposing in this theory is that instead of electing parties to then decide ministers and departments for the functioning of government, you elect people to perform specific functions in government.

80
00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:18.160
So you would elect a person with a legal background to be, say, the attorney general as far as managing the legal aspects of how the government operates and organizes the courts and that kind of system.

81
00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:44.120
You would elect a person with an economic background to be the minister for economics, the treasurer, et cetera, and the people would elect people based on their actual experience to do the job as that representative, and then direct the bureaucracy to perform that function based on their experience.

82
00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:48.560
Have you heard of anything like that before, or have you thought of anything like that before?

83
00:10:50.660 --> 00:10:52.600
They do that in the United states for judges.

84
00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:59.900
They get some real protests, but they elect judges, hanging judges and the courts people.

85
00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:05.980
But, so that's a very, that's a little subset.

86
00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:08.740
I don't know any other examples of them doing it elsewhere.

87
00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:21.520
The Athenians elected their, used elections very rarely, but they used them for their army commanders, who they called Streatygos.

88
00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:24.360
You can work out what words, what set of words we got from that.

89
00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:29.500
So they thought that merit was an important thing to choose there.

90
00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:34.860
But in very few other situations did they want to do that.

91
00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:46.580
Because Athenian democracy was predicated on the idea that it was in a kind of duel to the death with oligarchy.

92
00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:55.220
And it wasn't going to create the circumstances for oligarchs to get control.

93
00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.640
Which they did from time to time.

94
00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:03.460
Do you have any other comments, Yusuf?

95
00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:12.180
Well, Nicholas already mentioned the historical part of the Strategos.

96
00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:22.060
But what we should also add is that at the time when they did that, they also had sufficient drawing of lots for such positions because they thought it would be very egalitarian.

97
00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:32.160
I think, for Christ's sake already, that sortition is not a good principle.

98
00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:47.180
However, with election, and the way our media works today, this gets very much an election of a person, which I'm not sure is a good idea.

99
00:12:47.180 --> 00:12:55.740
What we're doing in economics today, or in business, is, okay, there are people who try to invent the smartphone.

100
00:12:55.740 --> 00:13:03.020
There is that company which does one run by one person, that company children, and then there is Apple with Steve Jobs.

101
00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:14.680
And in a way, what we do today already, is we, as buyers, as consumers, decide very democratically by what we buy, which phone we take.

102
00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:22.460
And obviously by consequence, the person was ingenious enough to invent it.

103
00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:31.220
So what I think will happen in our system of open democracy, if you remember on the left side, there was this ideation process.

104
00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:41.400
I think there will be people who carry forward ideas, solutions, which they think are good and can help society to collect these problems.

105
00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:57.120
And once the Citizen Parliament, which effectively is a statistical representation of the people, says yes, we take John Lowe's proposal to fix the issue of climate change, whatever.

106
00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:05.380
They elect the solution, irrespective of the person.

107
00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:14.380
And some people who are schooled in rhetorics know that it's a very illegitimate, sorry, how do you say that in English?

108
00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:23.680
It's not an allowed method to criticize something somebody proposes according to the person.

109
00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:28.860
It's a very bad idea, but our party election currently works like that.

110
00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:36.160
Any good politician has to be the type of man which every mother-in-law would be happy for her daughter to marry.

111
00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:38.900
That's what we say here, the mother-in-law is happy for her daughter-in-law.

112
00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:40.720
And it's party politics.

113
00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:43.740
It's too much about faces, too much about people.

114
00:14:43.740 --> 00:14:45.860
So we would be populating that problem.

115
00:14:45.860 --> 00:14:54.420
So no, I think what we should elect, what our citizens' samples should elect are good solutions, on the merit of dissolution.

116
00:14:54.420 --> 00:15:00.540
And I don't care if the person behind it is RKS, present model, and has a hub on his back.

117
00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:06.960
My question is just regarding interest groups.

118
00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:31.420
My biggest concern with our democracy at the moment is less about parties doing things in their own interests, but more to do with both parties doing what's in the interests of big donors and people who are gaming the system one way or another, like maybe the fossil fuel industry, donating money to politicians, and then they're just doing what the fossil fuel industry wants them to do.

119
00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:40.880
So it seems to me that it's not even the political system, that whatever system you get, it will be open to that kind of manipulation and corruption.

120
00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:45.100
And how would you stop that happening in your proposal?

121
00:15:50.640 --> 00:16:04.320
I mean, I think, so far as it's possible to stop it, I mean, I'd like to see stronger disciplines on funding and so on, but funding for the Citizens' Chamber is criminal.

122
00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:11.380
If you offer people money, it's criminal now to offer bribes to members of Parliament, I believe.

123
00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:14.300
Of course, it's not criminal.

124
00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:18.140
Well, it's not criminal to offer bribes to the party.

125
00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:29.660
But anyway, my point is that it's possible that somebody participates in a Citizens Jury and is taking money on the side.

126
00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:40.020
I don't think in all the experimentation with Citizens juries over the last 10 or so years around the world, we have an example of that, but it will happen from time to time.

127
00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:50.780
And it's a bit like some of those voting rules for judges in the Olympics if you build systems so that if there's one bad apple, it doesn't really make much difference.

128
00:16:50.780 --> 00:17:00.760
The point about a Citizens Jury is that there aren't incentives to take more notice of a well-funded supplicant than anybody else.

129
00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:09.020
I guess I was thinking a bit more broadly than just donating money, that parties put up stooges, but they can't in a Citizens Juries.

130
00:17:09.020 --> 00:17:14.099
Is branch stacking in the Labour Party or maybe I'm not sure in the Liberal Party?

131
00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:15.859
What's that got to do with the Citizens Jury?

132
00:17:15.859 --> 00:17:26.240
I'm just talking to do is in the selection process, how do we know that people won't use those kind of techniques to manipulate the selection process?

133
00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:27.940
Yeah, well, you clearly need...

134
00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:31.640
Yeah, it's an open process, it's an open process.

135
00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:40.640
So you clearly need a process of transparency where anyone at any stage can inspect the process.

136
00:17:40.640 --> 00:18:04.500
Now, in fact, we have that in electoral politics in the sense that I think I could convince you that there's very little crude electoral fraud in the sense that someone takes a vote for one party and says it's a vote for another, because behind them there are scrutineers.

137
00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:11.240
And those scrutineers are interested parties on both sides, and it works very well.

138
00:18:11.240 --> 00:18:19.120
Of course, it doesn't work through the whole, through the entire system, but that's all you need for a Citizens Juries.

139
00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:41.860
You need the scrutineers of the Labour Party and the Liberal Party and the Greens and One Nation and so on to clamber all over the process that they are assured, and a judge, and a retired judge and all the rest of it, to have the right to clamber all over the process by which those people on that jury were chosen.

140
00:18:41.860 --> 00:18:51.380
And they know, for instance, that this person was knocked out because while they were chosen at random, that would have produced too many men and not enough women.

141
00:18:51.380 --> 00:18:59.340
So we then took the 27 men and we just randomly picked 5 of them and got rid of them and so on.

142
00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:02.060
And people can see that process.

143
00:19:02.060 --> 00:19:13.460
So that's, I think, that it's sufficiently simple and technical that with the level of trust that we have in our society, we can do it well.

144
00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:16.800
If we were in Ghana, maybe not.

145
00:19:16.800 --> 00:19:21.600
You know, these are, you definitely need to take account of contextual factors.

146
00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:32.020
But I think in so far, in our society, we're very capable of delivering that degree of integrity and transparency.

147
00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:39.120
I think we can also just use the practical experience so far.

148
00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:44.660
I don't know about Australia, but I know certainly about Australia very intimately.

149
00:19:45.860 --> 00:19:52.680
The possibility of interest groups to corrupt the decision-makers are enormous.

150
00:19:54.320 --> 00:20:05.920
And if there's only the tip of the iceberg in the open, I mean, we're talking like a project, we need to buy some like 12 fighter jets.

151
00:20:05.920 --> 00:20:18.060
They're about 100 million euros, 150 million Australian dollars were sidetracked to a little count in this, in Bergenland, officially now.

152
00:20:18.080 --> 00:20:28.500
And so the interest groups know how to buy politicians, and they have developed fantastic structures by which you can, it's very, very hard for the money.

153
00:20:29.700 --> 00:20:32.720
So the evidence on the current system is clear.

154
00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:39.280
On the other hand, the evidence on the Citizens Juries so far is fantastic with regards to the other direction.

155
00:20:39.280 --> 00:20:44.140
For instance, take the example of the Irish Citizens Juries regarding abortion.

156
00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:59.520
The Catholic Church in Ireland and some other interested groups had been holding politicians hostage for decades, not to allow that even in very harsh cases.

157
00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:10.520
And, yeah, the Church could do nothing to impress the 100 citizens which were chosen randomly to vote their belief according to the situation.

158
00:21:10.520 --> 00:21:23.500
So the Irish Citizen Jury actually did finally react and allow mothers in certain dire situations the freedom to choose rather than to go to some heck and die.

159
00:21:25.840 --> 00:21:34.020
Thanks, Hubertus, I want to sort of maybe go into a brief kind of debate if you like.

160
00:21:34.020 --> 00:21:43.460
First, I mean, I want to say that I agree with a great deal of what you've said, and I want to ask a question and also offer a criticism.

161
00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:49.760
The question is about, I mean, well, I'll make an observation.

162
00:21:49.880 --> 00:21:56.700
As far as I, there is no way that you can make predictions about what is the case.

163
00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:05.320
Those are not direct observations of how good somebody's argument is about what should be the case.

164
00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:07.560
You've got an resort problem.

165
00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:09.280
You follow what I'm saying?

166
00:22:13.940 --> 00:22:23.060
Okay, so could you clarify how you, what the function of the, what sort of predictions are made?

167
00:22:24.940 --> 00:22:31.420
And what's the fun, how are they, how do they work in, on your platform?

168
00:22:31.440 --> 00:22:33.040
I'd be very interested.

169
00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:39.300
Each of them is very different.

170
00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:48.000
The question what is, is best captured by measurement, and in the absence of measurement by traditional questionnaires.

171
00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:55.520
The question what will be is best captured by the mechanism which I presented before.

172
00:22:55.520 --> 00:23:14.180
And the question what shall be is best answered by citizen juries, because to decide what shall be, you need to combine the expectation of what will be under certain conditions of the various paths which we can take.

173
00:23:14.180 --> 00:23:16.260
So if we do A, what will happen?

174
00:23:16.260 --> 00:23:17.700
If we do B, what will happen?

175
00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:19.880
If we do C, what will happen?

176
00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:25.940
And it's not enough to just have a consensus on the prediction market, what it will be, what happened.

177
00:23:25.940 --> 00:23:31.660
You also need to put in people's value judgment, the preferences before deciding.

178
00:23:31.660 --> 00:23:40.520
So you can only put to the people in the Citizen Parliament, well, in the Citizen Jury in your words, whether they want A, B or C.

179
00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:53.060
So the shell decision goes to the big Citizen Jury, the will prediction, the prognostics goes to the prediction market, and the what is question, the diagnostics goes to a public questionnaires.

180
00:23:54.220 --> 00:24:12.940
Okay, okay, but that, see, my problem, not so much with yours, but with yours, this seems to be a huge conundrum for us, is that it's very difficult to separate out high quality argument from low quality argument.

181
00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:35.820
And people fell in love with prediction markets at about the time that this problem asserted itself most forcefully because of course the prediction markets came in with, became very popular with the internet, Google was running internal prediction markets and so on.

182
00:24:35.820 --> 00:24:44.420
And lots of people were saying, rather like Joe Trippy was saying, that giving the people more direct access is going to solve these problems.

183
00:24:44.920 --> 00:25:00.440
They were saying that these prediction markets that have these miraculous qualities of being able to predict the future, of predicting the future, is as I think we agree, not the same as indicating what one's values are.

184
00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:07.080
So they don't make as big a contribution as we, I think we might both like them to make.

185
00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:24.540
Well, Nick, let me tell you, there is no such thing as this prediction market, just as much as there's no such thing as this democracy or this search engine.

186
00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:33.300
There used to be search engines like Metacrawler, Yahoo used to be a search engine, there's Bing, but then there's Google.

187
00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:34.720
So it really depends how you do it.

188
00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:55.820
It's the same on democracy, there's representative democracy, there's deliberative democracy, there's direct democracy, there's liquid democracy, there's 5,000 flavors of democracy, and ultimately somebody needs to develop a better mousetrap, which then works better, just like Google works better than other search engines.

189
00:25:55.820 --> 00:25:57.380
And it's the same with prediction markets.

190
00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:00.400
So, yes, I agree.

191
00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:03.600
Most of the stuff which you can find out is absolute crap.

192
00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:12.980
It doesn't serve more than, let's say, forecast elections, but you cannot use it for forecasting, let's say, subject matters.

193
00:26:12.980 --> 00:26:21.620
That's the reason I developed, here with my team, Prediki, because it is able to distinguish arguments.

194
00:26:21.620 --> 00:26:24.940
And I'll just show you again, maybe that got lost.

195
00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:29.200
Here, if I share my screen.

196
00:26:36.060 --> 00:26:41.220
For instance, if I go here now into education.

197
00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:50.980
I showed you before this, this, actually I have one analysis open here.

198
00:26:50.980 --> 00:26:58.540
Yeah, the system does find out which is the important argument, which are the less important argument.

199
00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:09.200
And effectively, it does that by going, and now by using text analysis algorithms, by going through all the arguments which are being made.

200
00:27:09.200 --> 00:27:14.480
yes, and of course, you can't do that on Twitter, because on Twitter you have 140 characters.

201
00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:23.660
You saw yourself what happens if you write longer messages, analytical messages on whatever system that was, wherever you argued on.

202
00:27:24.100 --> 00:27:29.800
But here, people write long arguments and they explain what they see in the system.

203
00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:40.860
And the crowd itself is able, by rating these arguments plus and minus, so it's not just like you like it, like on Facebook it's, I'm for it, I'm against it.

204
00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:45.000
They are able to distinguish whether an argument is good or bad.

205
00:27:45.560 --> 00:27:50.680
So it's, I'm saying short, that prediction markets don't exist.

206
00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:54.760
It very much is important how you do it.

207
00:27:54.800 --> 00:27:58.080
And yeah, so I think we do it very well.

208
00:27:58.080 --> 00:28:04.400
So if you have a campaign, politics is full of campaigns.

209
00:28:04.400 --> 00:28:21.160
And if you have a campaign for same-sex marriage or anything else, people will flood onto your platform and they will seek to influence what the platform is deciding.

210
00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:24.240
Is the important arguments and so on.

211
00:28:24.240 --> 00:28:26.620
So how do you deal with that?

212
00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:32.760
By openness.

213
00:28:32.760 --> 00:28:35.220
Since everything is transparent, it's open.

214
00:28:35.240 --> 00:28:37.920
And Hubert what?

215
00:28:38.380 --> 00:28:40.140
And what the arguments behind it.

216
00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:44.540
Everybody who doesn't like an argument can vote it down, can bring his own argument.

217
00:28:44.540 --> 00:28:50.000
If he votes it down, it's a matter of politeness, to also give a reason and to argue it.

218
00:28:51.100 --> 00:28:56.440
And this is what got Marijuana to the top of the list in the United states.

219
00:28:56.700 --> 00:29:05.700
Do what the Citizen Parliaments then do in the classically deliberative format, which is pretty much exactly as you go.

220
00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:09.600
I think it's well-known already in Australia.

221
00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:09.960
Yeah.

222
00:29:09.980 --> 00:29:11.200
Okay.

223
00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:17.480
So that's zero doubt that anything has happened there.

224
00:29:18.540 --> 00:29:24.500
If you want, I can show you afterwards the report, which was produced from that.

225
00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:26.680
Let me just see whether I have that here for you.

226
00:29:27.380 --> 00:29:30.240
The report, which was produced for the argument.

227
00:29:30.240 --> 00:29:36.220
And because we are combining four methodologies, I'll make this a little bit bigger here.

228
00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:46.360
It's effectively almost impossible to influence this in any particular way.

229
00:29:46.360 --> 00:29:51.700
So here, I can show you this in German, dissatisfaction with government by subject.

230
00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:54.960
And here it says, for instance, education.

231
00:29:54.960 --> 00:30:00.080
You can see how a traditional poll says education is not a problem.

232
00:30:00.080 --> 00:30:06.680
But once you apply the prediction market to a representative cohort, they say it is a problem.

233
00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:10.680
So how does, can you explain how the prediction market works to do that?

234
00:30:10.780 --> 00:30:13.180
Because I don't understand how to talk about education.

235
00:30:13.180 --> 00:30:16.100
They will also say it's a problem, open five.

236
00:30:16.100 --> 00:30:20.500
And if you then put them into a prediction market, they will also say it's a problem.

237
00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:24.660
So the methodologically robustness is enormous.

238
00:30:24.660 --> 00:30:27.720
And you can check that and the correlations are really high.

239
00:30:27.720 --> 00:30:29.680
So we can actually prove it, well, prove it.

240
00:30:30.020 --> 00:30:39.260
That we can actually document empirically that the outcome is extremely representative of the general expectation.

241
00:30:40.300 --> 00:30:48.540
So when you say that education is a problem, that is a value statement, not a predictive statement.

242
00:30:48.540 --> 00:30:54.340
So could you explain what you mean when you say that this is calibrated against prediction?

243
00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:57.640
We do prediction questions in various ways.

244
00:30:57.660 --> 00:31:07.160
And one of the ways we have invented, so to say, is something which we call a reflexive question.

245
00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:13.480
Very left-footed people predict what the survey will say is important.

246
00:31:13.480 --> 00:31:22.940
Because if you ask people in the survey, how often in the year do you exceed the speed limit, you will get an answer.

247
00:31:22.940 --> 00:31:28.280
Well, maybe 5% of people exceed the speed limit.

248
00:31:28.280 --> 00:31:39.300
But if you let people predict, please predict how many people in this year will exceed the speed limit, then you will get much, much higher numbers.

249
00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:41.260
And of course we know which one is true.

250
00:31:43.540 --> 00:31:43.820
Thanks.

251
00:31:43.820 --> 00:31:55.520
I just had a question because I actually really support the idea of Citizens Juries and I have a lot of faith in Australian people actually getting together and making decisions.

252
00:31:55.520 --> 00:31:58.920
It's the government, I don't have any faith in.

253
00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:04.880
But my question is, who will be asking the questions?

254
00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:09.740
Like who says that gay marriage should be on the agenda?

255
00:32:10.140 --> 00:32:21.780
I mean, if the politicians listen to the polls, they would have looked at NewsPoll back in 2007, 2010, which says 70% of Australians were in support of it anyway.

256
00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:34.020
But they're mainly a thing because it's someone's kind of agenda, perhaps making everyone look over there while something else is happening.

257
00:32:34.600 --> 00:32:40.620
So, Citizen juries can deal with issues, but are they dealing with the right issues?

258
00:32:40.620 --> 00:32:46.100
And how do they get access to that kind of higher level of what's actually happening?

259
00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:51.760
We did it in a very simple way.

260
00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:59.960
The first Citizen Jury, which we did, was asked the question, which are the important subjects?

261
00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:06.060
Let's just see.

262
00:33:06.060 --> 00:33:08.680
A whole battery of subjects.

263
00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:09.840
One second.

264
00:33:10.940 --> 00:33:13.180
Actually, you see me in the face.

265
00:33:13.180 --> 00:33:19.260
Anyway, we asked the whole battery of subjects divided by each ministry which exists in the government, each department of the government.

266
00:33:19.680 --> 00:33:24.780
And so, how happy are you with how that department works for the citizenship?

267
00:33:24.780 --> 00:33:33.700
And so, we got the ranking of where is the biggest dissatisfaction, including of course, with our system, the reasons why the word is satisfied.

268
00:33:33.700 --> 00:33:45.840
And then we put the citizen parliament in charge to decide, and it was just one day in effect, very fast, which is currently, in this moment, the most important issue.

269
00:33:45.840 --> 00:33:47.620
And that's the sequence by which we go.

270
00:33:48.460 --> 00:33:54.300
these guys, in the morning, they decided the biggest issue is actually the World Cafe Cup.

271
00:33:54.400 --> 00:34:05.900
I know it was in an open space type of format, by simply ranking those issues with a certain vote, a format which you call systemic consensus.

272
00:34:05.900 --> 00:34:14.040
And then in the afternoon, for the topic which they picked, they went in a World Cafe style, like on several tables, into depths.

273
00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:20.500
They had to go, what is the biggest problem in that sector?

274
00:34:20.500 --> 00:34:25.219
What are the solutions which the next citizen parliament has to look into?

275
00:34:25.219 --> 00:34:29.080
What type of information must be clarified in parallel?

276
00:34:29.080 --> 00:34:31.400
What are the chances if we do this right?

277
00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:37.920
What's the problems if we fail to fix this, if we continue doing nothing?

278
00:34:37.920 --> 00:34:41.219
And that, again, that was the brief for the next project.

279
00:34:41.860 --> 00:34:53.300
So, in the next project, the questions which were asked in the survey in the prediction market were designed according exactly to the instructions which the citizens have given us.

280
00:34:58.240 --> 00:35:34.340
I was just wondering, if or when you managed to get a representative into your parliament, how is it going to work with the current parliament working with the normal representative there, a shift to be an autonomous actor inside the parliament, whereas in this case, you're actually electing someone just to specifically be a mouthpiece or something that's happening on the internet.

281
00:35:37.480 --> 00:35:38.900
How will that work?

282
00:35:42.420 --> 00:35:54.560
It's a very good question because as in many countries in the world, the parliamentarians, for a very good reason, should speak their own mind and not be barren.

283
00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:58.180
That's the rule which we all know and which is a very good rule.

284
00:35:58.180 --> 00:36:12.960
And what we in fact are doing with the citizen parliaments is with bringing that back because everybody in the citizen parliaments can vote exactly to their own personal value, judgment and opinions.

285
00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:20.820
And you are right, in the traditional parliaments, that the representatives of guild should vote according to the citizen parliaments.

286
00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:23.000
But it wasn't us who did that.

287
00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.140
They do that already in parliaments.

288
00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:43.980
Like in reality, in the Austrian parliaments, it would be enough currently if there were five people sitting and each, whenever there is a vote, holding up a little poster saying, okay, I want with 43 votes, I want with 76 votes, because that's how they do it.

289
00:36:43.980 --> 00:36:53.860
The party leadership determines how these guys are supposed to vote and they do it because if they don't do it, they won't be on the list next time to be elected to parliament.

290
00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:56.820
They had a nice salary.

291
00:36:56.820 --> 00:36:59.400
So the parliament already is undermined.

292
00:37:00.740 --> 00:37:11.660
We have to apologize that this is not just frivolous, it just happens to make the iron law only got reverse, but there's a reason for it.

293
00:37:11.660 --> 00:37:16.200
The reason is that when this was designed, this was the age of agriculture.

294
00:37:16.200 --> 00:37:25.440
80 percent of people were working pretty much in the same industry, everybody else was maybe a soldier to fight the next war, or to conquer the next farmers.

295
00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:27.480
So everything was very simple.

296
00:37:27.480 --> 00:37:31.860
Nowadays, they all have to work in what you call the committees.

297
00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:45.600
The committees of only five people, the party representatives meet together, and then every party decides their stance, and it goes back to the party, and then it goes back to the 87 parliamentarians.

298
00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:55.560
So the system is already broken, and nobody is voting their own autonomous vote anymore, because it wouldn't work anymore because of the complexity.

299
00:37:55.560 --> 00:37:59.840
So what we are doing is bringing it back, because in the citizen parliament, everybody votes his own.

300
00:38:01.880 --> 00:38:23.500
With, say, if the representative from Jut was to get in, how would you, is there any way apart from the honest system to find them to make sure that they represent the system instead of their own vote until they get ousted in the next election?

301
00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:30.380
Can you repeat the question some other time, to physically understand it?

302
00:38:32.780 --> 00:38:55.580
So, if you're, if, say, the member of the guild's representative was to be put, placed into the parliament, they would have been elected on the assumption that they were going to follow through with what the system was, how the system wanted them to go.

303
00:38:55.580 --> 00:39:07.260
Is there any way, I assume there's no way in the current workings of the government to actually police that they did actually follow that consensus?

304
00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:10.380
They could actually turn around and...

305
00:39:12.700 --> 00:39:16.280
I guess you can release it.

306
00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:17.500
Can you repeat that again, sir?

307
00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:26.140
And second of all, I think, first of all, those people who are put in parliament as candidates have to commit it.

308
00:39:26.140 --> 00:39:28.880
There is a piece in writing.

309
00:39:28.900 --> 00:39:41.420
yes, it's more a moral obligation, but I think apart from the moral obligation, the best thing which is happening is that this citizen parliament, in fact, expresses the will of the people.

310
00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:51.140
And what's better for a parliamentarian to know exactly what the people of the very good deliberative format have come up with as a solution.

311
00:39:51.140 --> 00:39:56.480
Those people will feel very good about what they are bringing in parliament.

312
00:39:56.480 --> 00:40:09.340
Because maybe the members of the opposition, or of the governing parties, will feel very bad because they know they are buying the 12 fighter jets because of some shady deal between the prime minister and...

313
00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:14.180
So we just missed your first...

314
00:40:14.720 --> 00:40:17.180
You've added the two points.

315
00:40:17.180 --> 00:40:18.140
I've got the second point.

316
00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:22.340
We just missed the first because of our internet problem.

317
00:40:25.560 --> 00:40:26.360
There are two points.

318
00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:33.180
First of all, these people sign a declaration that they will vote according to the outcome of the Citizen Parliament.

319
00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:39.260
They do that in front of a group of the friends and family.

320
00:40:39.260 --> 00:40:41.500
They give this oath.

321
00:40:41.500 --> 00:40:42.140
It's an oath.

322
00:40:42.140 --> 00:40:44.620
It's bound or not.

323
00:40:44.620 --> 00:40:46.600
Yeah, like, if there was just one...

324
00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:49.280
Yeah, I mean, it's party discipline.

325
00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:50.540
Maybe that's what came through.

326
00:40:50.720 --> 00:40:53.020
I think that even stronger...

327
00:40:53.020 --> 00:41:08.620
It's not just only one as important, but it's also the factual reason that what they are to vote is what a representative sample of Austrian citizens decided using the value judgements.

328
00:41:08.620 --> 00:41:09.720
I think this is going to be much...

329
00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:15.460
You actually have a fantastic example of that in Australia, in South Australia, just besides you guys.

330
00:41:16.460 --> 00:41:25.280
You may have heard about this nuclear side killing citizen jury, the largest project of what New Democracy ever did, 300 people.

331
00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:26.340
Okay, got it.

332
00:41:26.340 --> 00:41:27.080
You guys know that?

333
00:41:27.080 --> 00:41:29.180
Yeah, yeah, yeah, well, I know.

334
00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:40.360
So what happened is the citizen jury looked at these proposals by the government, Jay Matherville, the prime minister's name is there with you guys.

335
00:41:40.360 --> 00:41:54.780
They looked at that, they heard the people who were for it, they heard the people who were against it, and in the end, I think they decided this is a vast super majority of 70 percent of more, no, we don't trust the government to do this nuclear thing.

336
00:41:54.800 --> 00:41:59.460
And what did Mr. Matherville do when it was decided in November of last year?

337
00:41:59.460 --> 00:42:06.120
He goes out and says, okay, this is just 300 people who knows who they are, who's paid them, we're going to do a referendum.

338
00:42:08.400 --> 00:42:19.820
And I think the way I read it, and Nick maybe followed this more closely than I, but I think in the end, the public argument is are you completely mad?

339
00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:25.400
There's 300 people who feel that every aspect of that, who look into it in detail, who discuss it for months.

340
00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:34.640
And now, you want an emotional media-driven referendum with a vote from everybody who had the African nuts.

341
00:42:34.640 --> 00:42:40.840
And I think in about June this year, he can this time stop all the referendum talk.

342
00:42:40.840 --> 00:42:44.300
There will be no referendum, there will be no nuclear thingy.

343
00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:54.180
Yeah, I think that that might be a bit, but I'm not sure that he did come out and call for a referendum after the jury.

344
00:42:54.480 --> 00:42:55.960
But he certainly...

345
00:42:56.920 --> 00:42:57.920
I can show you the internet.

346
00:42:57.920 --> 00:42:58.280
Okay.

347
00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:01.380
Before I do that, I'd be interested to see it.

348
00:43:01.380 --> 00:43:02.560
It's certainly...

349
00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:04.600
But I think the...

350
00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:18.880
What you say is right that the events illustrate the political power of a consensus arrived at by a Citizens Juries.

351
00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:20.300
So I agree with that.

352
00:43:31.200 --> 00:43:32.920
We were just expecting a question.

353
00:43:32.920 --> 00:43:33.200
Yeah.

354
00:43:33.200 --> 00:43:34.320
Well, I was even...

