00:43:34.320 --> 00:43:36.440
There was a comment on that question.

356
00:43:36.440 --> 00:43:37.100
Well, no.

357
00:43:37.100 --> 00:43:37.840
Yeah.

358
00:43:37.840 --> 00:43:38.940
I don't think I was...

359
00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:39.960
I wasn't going to ask the question.

360
00:43:39.960 --> 00:43:41.820
Did you catch that?

361
00:43:41.820 --> 00:43:44.660
Did you catch that, what I said?

362
00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:46.900
Yeah.

363
00:43:46.900 --> 00:43:47.260
Yeah, yeah.

364
00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:49.760
We sort of agree.

365
00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:51.580
We agree about the moral.

366
00:43:51.580 --> 00:43:53.800
I'm not sure about the facts and we're going to...

367
00:43:53.800 --> 00:43:55.180
You're going to correct me.

368
00:43:55.180 --> 00:43:56.680
I might be wrong.

369
00:43:56.680 --> 00:43:58.940
I just wanted to ask you...

370
00:44:03.860 --> 00:44:12.060
I'm not sure that I fully understood your concept of Citizens' Dury and how that was different to our other speaker.

371
00:44:13.160 --> 00:44:18.720
So, my understanding is you're saying the Senate itself should be kind of Citizens' Dury.

372
00:44:18.720 --> 00:44:22.520
Is that correct or...

373
00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:27.520
Well, I'm quite relaxed about that.

374
00:44:27.540 --> 00:44:32.320
I want a Citizens' Chamber to be part of our Parliament.

375
00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:35.260
If somebody says the...

376
00:44:36.040 --> 00:44:42.620
And then, you know, if you're suggesting this, you know, it's the sort of obvious way debates go.

377
00:44:42.620 --> 00:44:50.260
Someone will tell you, well, the Senate is pretty good at doing certain things like reviewing legislation, a point with which I agree.

378
00:44:50.260 --> 00:44:55.300
So, I don't mind if my chamber goes in addition.

379
00:44:56.560 --> 00:45:09.660
Essentially, what I see is important is some kind of citizen oversight of the Parliament, of the whole Parliamentary paper.

380
00:45:09.900 --> 00:45:31.060
I was going to ask Hubert what he thought about modest majorities on a Citizens Juries, because if you've only got 42 people and it splits 55-45, you don't have any great confidence that that's not a random phenomenon.

381
00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:34.520
And in fact, we recognize that in juries.

382
00:45:34.520 --> 00:45:51.940
So in juries, I don't think there's a constituents, I don't think there's a jurisdiction anywhere in the world that regards anything less than 9 out of 12 as anything that are hung durable.

383
00:45:51.960 --> 00:45:53.780
And I have a similar view.

384
00:45:53.780 --> 00:46:01.580
So my chamber would be able to govern itself with a 51-49 majority.

385
00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:09.540
It would be able to decide whether it moved on to this bill or that the speaker no longer be heard and all those kinds of things.

386
00:46:09.540 --> 00:46:15.020
But yeah, procedural matters, it would be its own master.

387
00:46:15.020 --> 00:46:28.200
But if it wanted to, and I also wouldn't mind giving it say a three month delaying power just to give the other house or houses an incentive to take it seriously.

388
00:46:28.300 --> 00:46:35.040
And we do that with the House of Lords in the UK, which has a one year delaying power.

389
00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:44.660
But I want to ramp up the power that a Citizens' Chamber has, when it can deliver a 60 or 65 percent majority.

390
00:46:44.660 --> 00:46:55.660
And then I have an extremely tricky, I think, thing that the very first thing it can do is it can compel a secret ballot of the other chamber or chambers.

391
00:46:56.440 --> 00:47:03.120
And a lot of these problems that we have right now, the problem we've had with guard pricing would never have been possible.

392
00:47:03.120 --> 00:47:13.420
Because it was a line ball thing anyway, and there would have been plenty of defectors if they knew they were safe in not being detected.

393
00:47:13.420 --> 00:47:22.580
And secondly, you can use things like we have in our Constitution, Section 57 of our Constitution allows for joint cities and things like that.

394
00:47:22.580 --> 00:47:27.000
So that's the sort of mechanism that I want to bring about.

395
00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:32.540
And the very fact that you can end up in that mechanism means it's a bit like wars.

396
00:47:32.540 --> 00:47:36.600
The fact that you can end up in one means that you avoid a lot of them.

397
00:47:37.960 --> 00:47:50.340
So parliamentarians who know that that's the fate of this will want to court the considered opinion of the people, not just the opinion of the people.

398
00:47:50.340 --> 00:47:54.080
So that's the kind of dynamic that I'm trying to bring about.

399
00:47:54.080 --> 00:47:59.180
I also think that there's something...

400
00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:11.440
I mean, if you've been part of political campaigns as I have, politicians and their operatives are terrified of the people and they're trying to give them everything they want.

401
00:48:12.120 --> 00:48:20.000
Now, it's also true that they're a bit terrified of their funders, so it's not a completely open possibility set that they're picking from.

402
00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:27.960
But this idea that politicians aren't trying to give people what they want, you just sit in a campaign committee meeting.

403
00:48:27.960 --> 00:48:41.900
I'm on the campaign committee of Gavin Newsom, who's running for governor in California, and they're just obsessed with can we spend our money giving it away on housing mortgages or power prices or whatever.

404
00:48:41.920 --> 00:48:45.220
And it's sort of as you would expect.

405
00:48:45.840 --> 00:48:55.840
So this whole idea that politicians are somehow satisfying their own interests, well, they are satisfying their own career interests.

406
00:48:55.840 --> 00:48:57.840
There's no doubt about that.

407
00:48:57.840 --> 00:49:07.360
But we've got ourselves a bogeyman, that if you look at it in a hard-headed way, is the wrong bogeyman.

408
00:49:07.360 --> 00:49:09.140
And these people are not on high salaries.

409
00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:11.260
They're having miserable lives.

410
00:49:11.260 --> 00:49:14.320
They're egotists who got into this game.

411
00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:19.320
They're egotists and idealists often who got into this game because they have a sort of set of ideological beliefs.

412
00:49:20.280 --> 00:49:22.940
They want to be well-regarded by their community.

413
00:49:22.940 --> 00:49:25.760
And here they are in this toxic show.

414
00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:28.220
And they're trying their best.

415
00:49:28.220 --> 00:49:31.760
And they're trying to come up with whatever they think that people will vote for.

416
00:49:32.380 --> 00:49:44.200
So, when Hubert says that his citizen chamber will somehow reveal what the people want, well, I think that that's kind of true.

417
00:49:44.200 --> 00:49:56.680
But remember that in political combat, in our system, the considered opinion of the people amounts to nothing unless people respect it and pay it legitimacy.

418
00:49:56.680 --> 00:50:03.120
Because in political battle, you'll have all the press and all the soundbites and all the rest of it.

419
00:50:03.120 --> 00:50:26.640
So, if the considered opinion of the people is that we should have a New South wales drug court style mechanism where we don't just put people in jail for 10 years for a drug offense, but we work quite intensively with them to try to solve their problem and in many ways treat it much more as a medical thing.

420
00:50:26.640 --> 00:50:29.000
You try that on with the shock jobs.

421
00:50:29.380 --> 00:50:31.120
You try that on the hustings.

422
00:50:31.120 --> 00:50:36.100
You try that when people got their sound bites after you.

423
00:50:37.660 --> 00:50:49.100
So that we have to face up to the fact that the democracy we have actually does give us something pretty close to the will of the people and there's something toxic about it.

424
00:50:49.100 --> 00:50:55.920
So that's where I'm trying to build the legitimacy of this, what I sometimes call, slow democracy.

425
00:50:55.920 --> 00:51:01.540
Because I think if people saw it, they would have the sort of respect for it that they have for juries.

426
00:51:01.540 --> 00:51:10.340
And they would say, well look, those people, they're just like me, they thought about it a lot more than I have, and a good majority of them think that I'm going with it.

427
00:51:11.620 --> 00:51:12.720
Can I add to that?

428
00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:23.160
Ian Walker is a guest at one of our designing Open Democracy meetings, and he talked about what was the main factor in the acceptance of the outcomes for Citizens Juries.

429
00:51:23.160 --> 00:51:30.020
And basically, it was whether beforehand in the press, they were able to see that the people of the Citizens juries Were like them.

430
00:51:30.020 --> 00:51:30.940
Were like them, exactly.

431
00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:41.540
Yeah, and that was like, Yeah, and so, like it was harder to dismiss because they've already been humanized as like regular people.

432
00:51:41.540 --> 00:51:47.720
But if they didn't do that beforehand, their outcome would kind of just be rejected out of hands.

433
00:51:47.720 --> 00:51:59.220
But what Hubertus says is also the case, which is that if you go into a Democratic election and you say the sort of things I've said or Hubertus said, it doesn't cut the mustard.

434
00:51:59.220 --> 00:52:01.120
Because people want to know about their mortgage rates.

435
00:52:01.220 --> 00:52:03.940
They think that elections are kind of auctions.

436
00:52:05.360 --> 00:52:09.860
And so, you know, there's a lot.

437
00:52:09.860 --> 00:52:11.860
So this is a hard road.

438
00:52:11.860 --> 00:52:14.160
And that's why I want to use...

439
00:52:14.160 --> 00:52:22.820
See, the difference between me and Ian Walker is, as I've said to Luca Beltrano-Nettis, you're the good cop, I'm the bad cop, okay?

440
00:52:22.820 --> 00:52:26.920
I want to use Citizens juries as a form of political activism.

441
00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:38.680
What New Democracy does is it goes to one government after another and says, could we run a Citizens Jury for you to solve a little problem that you've got?

442
00:52:38.680 --> 00:52:39.720
Now, good on them.

443
00:52:39.720 --> 00:52:40.920
I'm not critical of them.

444
00:52:40.920 --> 00:52:42.480
I think they're great.

445
00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:46.580
But they've been doing it for a long time now.

446
00:52:49.500 --> 00:53:03.360
And doing that concedes the greater legitimacy for the system that we have and political change never happened without the hubris of people saying, I'm not taking it anymore.

447
00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:12.900
I'm going for another idea of what political change and what political legitimacy should look like.

448
00:53:12.900 --> 00:53:14.820
Here it is.

449
00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:18.600
That's what I want to do and I think it would have a big impact.

450
00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:20.240
Let me give you an example.

451
00:53:20.240 --> 00:53:45.840
In Oregon, they, very good on them, they got, in 2011, a bunch of people managed to get into the Oregon Constitution, a mechanism in which if there was a Citizens' initiated referendum, which is part of their Constitution, it is accompanied by a Citizens' Review.

452
00:53:45.840 --> 00:54:04.720
And a Citizens' Review is a jury, a Citizens' jury, that sits on the referendum question and decides how it's going to vote and provides a 300-word pricey of its case to argue one way or the other.

453
00:54:04.720 --> 00:54:09.920
Now, of course, there's never been a jury in the process where it voted 24-0.

454
00:54:11.140 --> 00:54:12.660
It's 24 people.

455
00:54:12.660 --> 00:54:17.340
So there's always a split, and there's always 300 words you can read one way or the other.

456
00:54:17.440 --> 00:54:20.400
But you know how people voted.

457
00:54:20.400 --> 00:54:27.420
Proposition 73 was for mandatory sentencing, an absolute classic of Vox Pop democracy.

458
00:54:27.700 --> 00:54:32.820
Seventy percent of people in Oregon were in favor of it.

459
00:54:32.820 --> 00:54:43.600
When the Citizens Juries sat, I presume roughly 70 percent of the 24 people were in favor going in and 30 percent against.

460
00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:57.640
The Citizens Jury wrote its advice out on both sides, but 21 people signed the case against voting yes, and three people signed the case for voting yes.

461
00:54:57.640 --> 00:55:04.880
And that, amongst other things, reduced the vote from 70 percent to, I think, 56 or 7.

462
00:55:04.880 --> 00:55:07.480
So the referendum got up.

463
00:55:07.480 --> 00:55:11.460
But that's a pretty encouraging story, I think.

464
00:55:11.460 --> 00:55:13.140
And so that's what I'm after.

465
00:55:13.340 --> 00:55:19.620
I'm after plonking this damn thing there and saying, look at that, that works better than you guys.

466
00:55:19.620 --> 00:55:21.460
Not can we be of service to you.

467
00:55:26.720 --> 00:55:27.960
I think we might leave it there.

468
00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:33.560
So thank you very much to those that have presented, Nicholas Gruen and Hubertus Hofkirchner.

469
00:55:33.560 --> 00:55:34.200
Thank you very much.

470
00:55:34.200 --> 00:55:42.160
Hi, and I hope you enjoyed this recording, and that you learned to feel more things about what the audience understood.

471
00:55:43.100 --> 00:55:56.500
So with that being said, if you have any feedback about this podcast, you could always contact us at contact at designingopendemocracy.com, or you could comment in our reveal page.

472
00:55:56.500 --> 00:55:58.720
Aside from that, enjoy your holidays.

473
00:55:58.720 --> 00:55:59.020
Cheers.